{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e6beaea7-dc97-4d6f-8bd0-51bf566db101","content":"Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`** — so there's nothing to migrate on that front. It's already safe for .NET 8 in that regard.\n\nHowever, the pattern of manually spawning `Thread` per work item is outdated. The modern .NET 8 approach:\n\n```csharp\npublic class SimpleWorker\n{\n    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)\n    {\n        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>\n        {\n            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);\n        });\n    }\n\n    private void Process(WorkItem item)\n    {\n        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 8. Your code doesn't call it, so you're fine.\n- **`Thread.Sleep`** → remove it if it was only simulating work; if you genuinely need a delay, use `await Task.Delay()`.\n- **Manual `Thread` creation** → prefer `Parallel.ForEachAsync` or `Task.Run` for automatic thread pool management and cancellation support via `CancellationToken`.\n- If you need cancellation (the main reason people used `Thread.Abort`), pass a `CancellationToken` and check `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `Process`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7302880e-5f03-4ea1-9c76-e2ca5718173e","outputTokens":352,"requestId":"D002:190179:19BEAD4:1D353A9:69E8235C"},"id":"b9e75a41-24c6-4e06-994d-4f24d0d11683","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:24:52.472Z","parentId":"0a31bc3e-b9d0-4171-a075-89fbc573e4b4"}
